# 📰 Fake News Detection

A complete, beginner-friendly machine learning project that classifies news articles as **FAKE** or **REAL** using classic NLP techniques (TF-IDF) and a Logistic Regression model, with an interactive Streamlit web app for live predictions.

---

## 📁 Project Structure

```
Fake-News-Detection/
│
├── dataset/
│   ├── Fake.csv          # Fake news articles (from Kaggle)
│   └── True.csv          # Real news articles (from Kaggle)
│
├── train.py              # Preprocesses data, trains model, evaluates, saves artifacts
├── app.py                # Streamlit web app for live predictions
├── model.pkl             # Saved trained Logistic Regression model (generated)
├── vectorizer.pkl        # Saved fitted TF-IDF vectorizer (generated)
├── requirements.txt      # Python dependencies
└── README.md             # This file
```

> **Note:** `model.pkl` and `vectorizer.pkl` are generated automatically when you run `train.py`. They are not meant to be edited by hand.

---

## 📦 1. Dataset Setup

This project uses the **Fake and Real News Dataset** from Kaggle:

🔗 https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/clmentbisaillon/fake-and-real-news-dataset

**Steps:**
1. Create a free Kaggle account if you don't have one.
2. Download the dataset (it contains `Fake.csv` and `True.csv`).
3. Unzip it and place both CSV files inside the `dataset/` folder, exactly as shown in the project structure above.

> A couple of tiny **sample** `Fake.csv` / `True.csv` files are included in this repo just so you can test that the code runs end-to-end. **Replace them with the full Kaggle files** for a real, accurate model — the full dataset has ~44,000 articles, while the included samples only have 24 (just for wiring-testing, not real accuracy).

